StudyInfo.StudyNameEntrez: Physiological, psychological, and genomic factors that predict the transition from acute to chronic pain in patients with traumatic lower extremity fracture

Policy.acknowledgement_statement: Funding support for the Physiological, Psychological, and Genomic Factors that Predict the Transition from Acute to Chronic Pain in Patients with Traumatic Lower Extremity Fracture study was provided by the National Institute of Nursing Research (R01NR017555). The dataset(s) used for the analyses described in this manuscript were obtained from the database of Genotypes and Phenotypes (dbGaP) found at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gap through dbGaP accession number (insert accession number). Genotype and associated phenotype data for the Physiological, Psychological, and Genomic Factors that Predict the Transition from Acute to Chronic Pain in Patients with Traumatic Lower Extremity Fracture study were provided by Principal Investigators Cynthia Renn, PhD, Susan Dorsey, PhD, and Mari Griffioen, PhD.

GSR_Access.gsr_mode_label: Unrestricted access (according to a new Institutional Certification)
